text: @G6 Hmmm ja, auch ein ganz netter Erkl√§rungsversuch, aber das eine schlie√üt das andere trotzdem nicht unbedingt aus. Es geht bei Tests nicht nur um die Reifen, obwohl das schwarze Gold nat√ºrlich extrem wichtig ist. Ferrari hatte zb. in der Vergangenheit eine ganz-ganz enge Kooperation mit Bridgestone. Da wurden die Reifen sozusagen ma√ügeschneidert. Andere Teams f√ºhlten sich sogar benachteiligt. (heute nat√ºrlich "nahezu" unm√∂glich) Aber wer wei√ü, was da f√ºr Daten hin und her geschoben werden. Man kann und muss ja so gut wie alles in der Praxis ausprobieren und da geh√∂rt die K√ºhlung, der Motor, Handling, Aerodynamik, Balance und unz√§hlige andere Dinge auch dazu. Und es wird wahrscheinlich auch kleine Hersteller geben die √§hnliches produzieren. Schau, wir d√ºrfen nicht in unseren kleinen Alltags Dimensionen denken. text: @Christian U. Es macht einfach keinen Sinn! Warum gehe ich auf eine Rennstrecke testen? Nat√ºrlich kann ein Team, und darum ging es ja von Anfang an, irgendwo geheim absetzten und fahren, aber der Aufwand und die eingeschr√§nkten und zum Teil verf√§lschten Daten machen ein solches Unterfangen Sinnlos. Il panorama della stagione 2019 si giocher√† sul filo dei secondi e dei punti, ma la forma della nostra livrea rossa √® tutta da scoprire; e ancora una volta sar√† fascinosa, imbarazzante, registrata perfettamente al nuovo che avanza e alla tecnologia insistente, e l'innovazione sar√† unica e inimitabile. La tradizione √® ispirazione, √® valore aggiunto nato da mani e menti emiliane, lavoratori dotati di tanta passione per l'armonia di un motore acceso e velocissimo, e la volont√† di essere la storia nella storia; di aver costruito pagine di vita sportiva, di aver partecipato a tutti i campionati del Mondo di formula 1 e di essere legati ad una generazione meccanica italiana. La Ferrari, il cuore rosso Ferrari √® l'esempio vivente, di una classe sportiva lunga e coerente, fatta di ricerca e sviluppo costanti, ma saldamente stretta al suo passato glorioso, evocativo e anche se sconfitta materia di ammirazione... comunque. Si alzano i veli della Ferrari f.1 2019 e il lustro italiano nel Mondo si riafferma... e noi tifosi siamo pronti a gioire e soffrire con il cuore rosso in gola. di Maurizio Spagna@ su "¬© ROCKABOLARIONman's" ¬©2019

author: Incitatus
text: All this talk of end-plates on every F1 car.. What happens when the driver adjusts their front wheel cambers and the tyres are then expanded outward from the end plate? I've seen on every car the end-plate is directly flush in-line with the side ends of the tyres... Air wash will essentially be directed to the sides of the tyres effectively creating more slip and less traction as well as increased cooling effect of the rubber which we know they dont want, essentially they want tyres up to optimal temperatures. I know certain tracks most drivers use a increased camber setting in which the inside part of the tyres are getting the bulk of the traction. Anyway, just my observation..

author: TKDI for life
text: I think they did 3 things mainly: 1-reproducing an ouwash effect with neutral/negative wing to control airflow out of tyre squirt/turbulence. 2-the middle of the front part raises air from the wing to the sodepods while the central vortexes are heavily outwashed by the barge boards. This probably undercuts the need of a slim area underneath the sodepods which is used to channel the flow inside the lateral structure. That large structure also prevents the ouwash to come too early into the sides of the car. 3-pushing hard to let the outwashed air come into the coke bottle area more violently and orderly. Similar to red bull they pushed the tightness to an unbelievable level and all that air that comes back into the car should hit hard the diffuser with a lot of pressure. Refines the concept of last year! It will be very interesting to see who will come on top!

author: Niko
text: @J√≥zsef Interesting take, thanks for your input. Judging by the comparisons I've been making between the two cars (Mercedes and Ferrari), it would seem that Mercedes is a tighter package around the rear lower section towards the suspension. Where as Ferarri seem to tighter at the mid-rear top of the engine cover section than the Mercedes, and wider around the rear section/suspension area. I can see an obvious area advantage to the Ferrari in that respect, particularly with regard to rear air-flow over the wing, and the subsequent downforce. What would be the advantage - if any - to Mercedes having a more tightly packaged area around the rear suspension?

author: ark13700
text: @J√≥zsef Compare the sizes of the shark fins. Ferrari's top air intake falls away much quicker than Merc's, hence the comments about tighter packaging. The triangular intake shape also cuts down the cross-sectional area significantly.

author: maverick buckley
text: I'm a big Seb fan and a Brit. Thinking about it my friends who are into F1 are all Seb fans. He's actually very British in his mannerisms, sense of humour and obviously he speaks with in English English rather than Canadian/American English. The only thing I would say is that the University of Sheffield built a software program that takes into account your record against ex team mates, ex rivals in the same series' and so on. So you don't get skewed results where someone who has only driven top tier cars comes out on top. Fangio was the best, Proxy, Senna,Alonso and Sterling Moss came in top 5. So going in a rudimentary style of that theory and using certain results from it, Seb lost a season to Danny Ricardo in the same car. Danny Lost a season (and the No.1 seat) to Max in the same car. So in theory over a season Max should be dominant over Seb. But we'll have to see how good the red bull is. Also interested to see SEB vs Charles LeClerc in the same car .

author: WestLAGuy
text: Obviously, I was joking, but given the sophistication of Formula 1 today it makes sense. The lighter the car, the faster it can go in relation to other equally powered engines. Making his cars lighter was what Colin Chapman was always after. That less weight made his cars less, shall we say, safe has been argued. However, no one knows what caused Jimmy Clark's Formula 2 Lotus to go off the track at Hockenheim on April 7, 1968 and Jochin Rindt's fatal crash at Monza in practice on Sept. 6, 1970 was attributed to brake failure and a badly mounted Armco barrier. Alan Henry's Rindt profile in Autocourse also states that Rindt was driving with no front wings per Chapman to find more speed and his six point harness was not connected .

text: Rory Coles, get some facts straight. Ferrari did have a "second wind" (sic), but only in qualifying (indicating a one off overheating). Benz were the first to burn oil, a complete cheat bypassing the very strict fuel flow regulations (FIndia and HAAS both banned in Canada for exceeding the fuel flow), that they weren't stopped after a couple of teams complained, forced other teams to do it as well. I would 100% agree there have been periods of time in F1 where teams have been favoured, Ferrari and Renault come immediately to mind, it is now Benz who are clearly being favoured, it's just a fact, and on a far bigger scale than most realise, and it's driving privateers like Williams, out

text: I don't understand the changing of tyre colours. It is supposed to make it easier to determine the which tyre is used, but now with testing there are so many mixed colours, that I have no idea which tyre is which!

author: GMC
text: For Testing: C1 - C2 - C3 - C4 - C5 C1 = Hardest tyre compound - White/No band around the tyre wall C2 = Hard tyre compound - White/Band around the tyre wall. C3 = Medium/Soft tyre compound - Yellow/Band around the tyre wall. C4 = Softer tyre compound - Red/Band around the tyre wall. C5 = Softest tyre compound - Red/No band around the tyre wall. There's also a black development tyre with no markings being trialed during testing too. Once the F1 season kicks off in Melbourne: Pirelli will bring three of those five compounds to each race and name them Hard, Medium and Soft, regardless of what C spec they actually are. So, theoretically it will be much easier for F1 followers to know which tyres each driver/team is using.

author: GMC
text: @LegendaryAiden You're welcome, friend. For the most part, teams have been running on the C2 or C3 in testing. Only a few of the teams have tried the C4 and C5 yet, I believe.

author: Lightning McQueen
text: Man Charles is gonna be good! After I watched a hand full of races of his in the junior categories I was convinced...The kid oozes greatness but unlike Max he possesses an uncanny calm and maturity... Gotta have both types of personalities which will keep the future of F1 interesting... They both are off the charts talented! "IF" the Ferrari is equal or better than the Mercedes, it is going to be an exciting season and Vettel better learn to keep his shit together because Charles WILL get the better of him @ the very least on a hand full of occassions. I personally think Vettel will crack..He has always had that problem where he (IN MY OPINION) all the way back into his Red Bull days puts way to much pressure on himself wth a mix of lack of confidence mixed with over confidence used with spoiled, mixed with raw emotion mixed with an undoubtable talent which forces mistakes. Prime example of all of that confusion together CANADA 2011 where last lap he had it in the bag and blew it for Jenson Button to have the craziest win in F1 history..He cracked in really a meaningless race in terms of the driver championship, wasnt a championship decider or anything. I don't think Seb will be able to have the protection from Leclerc as he did with Webber where Vettel could do whatever he wanted. If Charles starts / is allowed to race early on Vettel will undoubtedly crack..It isn't gonna be Lewis in a different team it will come from within and I don't think Ferrari will put up with the temper tantrums come contract renewal if Leclerc is showing he can consistanly challange Lewis, Max, vettel...

text: mstrchf 123 Vettel has been very disappointing for the last three years. Leclerc has done an amazing job in the GP2, his last year was impressive to. He is almost equally quick by the tests. Although Vettel will be a bit faster at the beginning, I think Leclerc is the faster one. Vettel is very vulnerable when the pressure is too high. He will be more under pressure than last year.

author: mstrchf 123
text: @#60 Legends Charles has pressure too this year. How is he going to handle that? We don't know. How is he gonna react when Vettel is often 0.3 faster in Q3. Seb gets pole, 0.3 slower you might be 4th on the grid. The whole race is different/difficult. The Ferrari might very well be the best car this year but if you qualify 4th you're in the mix with Verstappen, Hamilton etc...and might not get any places back. These people might own you even bringing more pressure. + every race you get this. Good car, underperforming...teammate better in qualifying therefore the race, there might be some crashes. Now you have to 'keep it clean' and go faster. At sauber people don't even see you were 0.3 slower in Q than optimal. who cares....still 4tenths faster than your average teammate. At Ferrari all the above things bring more pressure. In short i think it's a tough year for charles leclerc and vettel isnt that bothered. I actually don't think vettel is that sensitive to pressure. His style always been agressive, bordering stupid sometimes. But if you're close to the wdc you lose it at those moments. I bet you can go back through the years for vettel and find the same kind of reckless incidents in every season. I see that more as Vettel not giving a fuck. Also a luxury that leclerc doesn't have.

author: #60 Legends

author: Karl Owen Aurelio
text: TRUE!!! And since when did these so called "experts" ever got it right? I mean Ferrari have always been on top or near the top in testing! But as usual (or since 2014), Mercedes always bags the titles with races to spare! Most of us have been following the sport for a very long time yet some of us keep falling for the usual "traps" that testing results tell us. Lots of "experts" even come up with terms like "tire-corrected, "fuel-corrected"! Really??? Well, sure anyone can spot the tire used, that we can factor in easily. But, even with the C5 tire bolted on and the car does 2 or 3 laps sets a purple laptime and heads back to the pits, how do we know if the car had 3 laps worth of fuel? Was the engine mode aggressive? Was the battery discharge aggressive? Was the driver 100% pushing? Most know Mercedes sandbags alot! I do mean they probably are laughing at all these experts right now! We all know Mercedes never shows its true hand until Q3 of the first Grand Prix weekend. Also, the fact that Mercedes brought several new parts into Testing 2 just 4 days from the 1st Test means they have many iterations of the W10 readily available. They are simply just giving these parts a dry run!
